<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
We have 3 computers, mine runs 98SE but the other two run XP Home Ed. Both the XP comps are from Dell, while mine is home built. Anyway, both of the XP comps have gotten a problem with their paging file (both have the same problem, got it at different times though). When you boot up the computer, it has a message box like so: Your system has no paging file, or the paging file is too small.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This problem probably came about from a corrupt paging file, which can happen if Windows crashes or is not shut down properly.  When it boots back up, Windows has a cow and doesn't repair the paging file properly.<br>
<br>
Should be easy to fix.  First run scandisk to catch any corruption that's still hanging around on the drive.  Then go to Control Panel/System/Advanced and click on the performance settings button.  click on the Advanced tab and hit the Change button under Virtual Memory.  Change to &quot;custom size&quot; and put it at like min 2000 max 3000 or something like that (if you don't have that much free space on your drive consider making room).  Reboot and you should be OK.<br>
<br>
This is a good thing to do anyway--it will give you a much bigger paging file that Windows normally will set on its own, which can help when running EQ (especially if you don't have loads of RAM).<br>
<br>
I know you said you tried custom settings before, but make sure to do a scandisk first and super-size the settings and see if that helps.  Also make sure your C: drive has lots of free space or else you'll never have an adequate paging file.<br>
<br>
Shanuk Dandiprat<br>
Arch Mage of Drinal<br>
